{
  "doc_id": "32234",
  "text": "Adolescence is a critical developmental period for the maturation of neurobiological processes that underlie higher cognitive functions, as well as emotional and social behavior. The neurobehavioral systems that sub-serve these skills include inferior, orbital and dorsolateral portions of the prefrontal cortex (PFC) with rich interconnections to several limbic structures. The PFC matures later than other regions, and its development is paralleled by increased abilities in abstract reasoning, attentional shifting, processing speed and response inhibition. Simultaneously, changes in emotional capacity, including improvements in affective modulation and discrimination of emotional cues, also occur during adolescence [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
